interviewer_comment: Vasiliy is a candidate with good experience, nice soft skills, he is open, friendly and ready to keep the conversation going. The candidate's self-presentation was well-structured, detailed, contained all relevant information. Vasiliy was ready to speak about his strong and weak points, provided personal examples. Some points to consider: 1)remember how to deal with the situations when you don't know how to answer the question  2)make your answers as extensive as possible, it's your chance to present yourself in a brighter light  3)we use Present Perfect when we talk about experience, Past Simple for definite things that happened in the past  4)don't mix modal verbs (can/must/should) and auxiliaries together : I don't code vs I can't code. I wish Vasiliy good luck!

Illia is a strong candidate with good soft skills, he is open, friendly and keeps the conversation going. His self-presentation was well-structured, detailed and had all necessary and relevant information. Illia's English level is high enough to communicate with the interviewer in English. Some points to consider: 1)pronunciation of the words 'colleague, methodology'  2)behind vs except for   3)we can reach/ achieve our goals/aims/targets  4)motivating vs motivated.  I wish Illia good luck!

The candidate needs to improve the self-presentation (expand it with more of the details on your experience, achievements, impact). Try to show more enthusiasm and inspiration to be a part of the project. Prepare a few questions to the potential customer. Remember to to mention the result already reached while struggling with the weaknesses. Miminimize on the use of the gestures. Make sure that the camera is not shaking. Remember that at least 70% of the time tje eye contact is required to be kept. The English level needs to go through some improvement (grammar, vocabulary and the fluency of speech are to be improved). Thank you and do your best!

"The candidate has improved his performance a lot. He has managed to present himself in a good light and highlight his strengths. He prepared a brilliant self-presentation and handled most of the questions very well. Artiom is outgoing and friendly. His English is a bit faulty but very well comprehensible.
I'd just point out the following:
1. an interview is a formal conversation so one has to be careful with wording: swear words are unacceptable; it's better to ask questions starting with I'd like to know/I was wondering (rather than I wanna know)
2. try thinking of some situations from the experience that showcase the problem-solving skills (some technical problems/problems with people or team/with deadlines... or some mistakes that you've made). If you tell a story and explain how you solved the problem or what you've learnt thanks to it, it makes the answers more grounded and informative
3. see my comments regarding the English language in the previous message"

Artiom is a candidate with nice soft skills, he is open, friendly and ready to keep the conversation going. Still there are some points to take into account: 1)Check the structure of self-presentation one more time: here your task is to speak about your professional background and experience, briefly cover the companies and projects you were working on, finally you need to speak about your latest project in detail (make use of the STAR plan - situation/ task/ actions/ result+ you can mention here some challenges and how you dealt with them)  2)take care with the pronunciation of the words 'Bachelor/ retrospective/  3)remember that we use Present Perfect for sth that started in the past and is still going on  4)experience - is an uncountable noun   5)remember how to deal with the situation when you're not ready to answer the question (about design patterns or SOLID). I recommend Artiom having one more run so that he can feel more confident. I wish Artiom good luck!

The candidate is a professional with an extensive experience and background. He tries to do his best and keep the conversation going. Beka's speech is rather fluent and coherent. Yet I would recommend him to work on the pronunciation of some words given in the chat, use fillers (see them in the chat), expand vocabulary and work on verb patterns (infinitive), Conditional 3 and singular/plural forms of verbs. Regarding the presentation, he should work on the following action points: 1) use the structure of self-presentation (see it in the chat) and include the description of his tech stack; 2) make sure he sounds beneficial and does not criticize the employer or the product, thus he should sound more positive; 3) prepare the description of the strengths and provide work related examples; 4) point out YOUR roles and responsibilities on the projects. Besides, he should be more precise concerning the question 'Why are you a good fit for this position?' and provide a detailed answer. I would also recommend him to use a formal way of communication (avoid inappropriate words), keep eye contact and learn a bit more information about the project if possible. I suppose one more interview simulation is necessary to gain more experience. Good luck!

Yaroslav is a strong candidate with good soft skills, he is very friendly, open and ready to keep the conversation going. Still there are some points to pay attention to:1)remember to ask return questions to the interviewer, it makes communication more polite  2)some language points:  1. check pronunciation of the words 'event/applicable/manner;  2. to be LUCKY - use the adjective, not an adverb  3. 'time' is an uncountable noun  4.check the worder - to manage sth better  4. AT the weekend. I wish Yaroslav good luck!

Victor is a candidate with nice soft skills and good experience, he is open, ready to answer the questions, but needs a bit more confidence. I advise Victor to take all the points into account and good luck!

Arthur is a candidate with nice soft skills and personal qualities, he has quite good level of English. The candidate is a  friendly and sociable person, he is good at small talk; he is a professional with an extensive experience and background. His fluency is good enough, can make occasional pauses for reflection, he should use questions for clarification (given in the chat), use fillers and closing expressions mentioned above; remember about sequence of tenses, focus on quantifiers (many vs. much). Besides, here are some other action points to work on: 1) follow the structure of self-presentation (follow the link above) and mind its duration (4-5 min); 2) use STAR approach (follow the link above); 3) make sure you can describe your strenghts and provide work related examples; 4) describe your weakness(es) and say which way you are working on it/them; 5) make up 2 relevant questions for the customer and ask them in a polite way. In addition to that, I would like to recommend Roman to be more confident and try to reduce anxiety by relaxing before an interview. In general, I suppose one more interview simulation is necessary to brush everything up. Good luck!

"The candidate tries to do his best despite the fact that he is anxious. The flow of speech is mostly moderate, there can be some pauses for reflection, thus it is recommended to use fillers and linking expressions noted above. The candidate should focus on the following action points: 1) use STAR approach to describe his project experience and be quite precise in terms of HIS roles, tasks, activity and responsibilities; 2) structure the answers if the question is tricky (do not make them vague); 3) remember not to mention too many weaknesses (1-2 is enough); 4) try to take it easy and try to decrease anxiety before the interview. Besides, it is recommended to use closing expressions (That's it / That's all I wanted to say). He shouldn't focus too much on the fact that he hasn't got any experience concerning a certain technology.
In general, I would recommend him to have one more interview to master his soft skills and gain more confidence."

"The candidate is  a professional with extensive experience and background. He has good soft skills and can keep the conversation going. At the beginning of the interview he was a bit anxious, but futher he sounded quite confident. His language skills help him be understood with no difficulty. However, occasionally it happens that he can forget a word, yet he is skilled enough to find a way out. I would definitely recommend him to use questions for clarification (I’m sorry, could you say that again? / Could you explain what you mean by…?  Do you mean ..?) in case some words/ideas are not quite clear. Besides, it is important to use closing expressions (That's it / That's all I wanted to say / That's how I see it) to sound proficient; it is important to use expressions to 'buy' some time (Well, I can’t recall the situation like that at this moment, but it seems to  me that…/ I think, I’ve deﬁnitely had some situation like this, give me a sec to  recall). He should pay attention to his grammar and work on Conditionals 1-3 as well as countable (many issues) and uncountable nouns (some advice); pay attention to the pronunciation of some words( whole /həʊl/; company /ˈkʌmpəni/; methodology /ˌmeθəˈdɒlədʒi /; colleague /ˈkɒliːɡ/) and mind, please, verb and preposition patterns (listen to my colleagues; pay attention to smb); focus on expressions (develop my skills). As for the interview simulation, the candidate should work on the following action points: 1) use a closing expression at the end of the presentation (That's it. If you have any questions, I am ready to answer); 2) use STAR approach (see the example in the chat) and remember to mention the outcome of the project; 3) make sure you describe the way you are working on your weaknesses; 4) use a polite way of asking questions (Could you please tell me / I would appreciate if you tell me...). It is recommended to learn more information about the upcoming project.
In general, the impression is positive, despite having tech problems (which should be handled in advance). I believe the candidate is ready for an interview after dealing with the action points mentioned above. Good luck!"

The candidate is  a professional with extensive experience and background . He tries to do his best; in terms of  the language, he has no serious mistakes regarding pronunciation, yet there are some moments he has to focus on (mentioned above), it is recommended to pay attention to them. There are some other action points to focus on: 1) follow STAR approach (see it in the chat); 2) make sure you can describe the weaknesses and the way you are working on them (use the link in the chat); 3) prepare 2-3 questions for the customer (it is recommended to learn more information about the upcoming project if possible); 4) remember to use questions for clarification (I’m sorry, could you say that again? / Could you explain what you mean by…? / Do you mean ..?); 5) remember to use closing expressions (That's it / That's all I wanted to say). Besides, he should point out his roles and responsibilities on the projects and be more precise concerning the examples.  Dealing with tricky questions, try to sound beneficial and use expressions to 'buy' some time (Well, I can’t recall the situation like that at this moment, but it seems to  me that…./ I think, I’ve deﬁnitely had some situation like this, give me a sec to  recall…). It is a good idea to check the quality of sound, video and headset beforehand. I would like to recommend having one more interview simulation to make sure that the error correction work is done and the candidate is confident enough to keep the conversation going. Good luck!

In general, the interview performance was quite good. The candidate is a professional with an extensive experience and background. His soft skills are good enough. Yet, occasionally he can have difficulties answering tricky questions (e.g. the question about his greatest accomplishment and his strengths). He needs to highlight HIS roles and responsibilities on the projects. At the end of his self-presentation, there should be a closing expression (e.g. That's it. If you have any questions, I am ready to answer). Besides, it is important to use questions for clarification in case there's something unclear (I’m sorry, could you say that again? / Could you explain what you mean by…? / Do you mean ..? ). The candidate should be sure that he is aware of the project requirements to answer the questions 'Why are you a good fit for this position?' / 'What kinds of benefits can there be for you on the project?'. It is important to turn all the notifications off beforehand so that they do not distract the candidate, make sure the camera position and the pose are appropriate as well. In general, the candidate is almost ready, but I would recommend him to have one more interview simulation to gain confidence and work on minor issues mentioned above. Good luck!

I would also recommend him to learn a bit more information about the upcoming project if possible to feel confident in terms of the question 'Why are you a good fit for this position?'.
In general, I would recommend having one more interview simulation to gain confidence and make sure that the candidate has dealt with the action points mentioned above. Good luck!"

The candidate is ready for an interview with the customer after small improvements. Most of the blocks and skills are are of a high level, but some minor improvements are needed - keep the eye contact and remember to mention the ways you are working on your weaknesses in

Tofic is not ready for the job interview with a customer in English. Here are some points to pay attention to: 1)I recommend working on the self-presentation structure, as Tofic's presentation was very brief, in addition to that I advise to plan the speech about project experience beforehand in English, so that all information about stack, technologies is mentioned by the speaker himself  2)The candidate didn't seem to be interested in the talk/project/final result, I recommend being more enthusiastic about future opportunities  3)from the language part : we use Present Simple for characterics which are true now, Past Simple - for actions that finish in the past; mind pronunciation of the word 'component'   4)when you speak about best motivation at work - it's better not to mention money on the first place, stress your professional goals and ambitions  5)there were moment when you didn't know what to say - you may use some fillers 'Let me think/ This is a nice/difficult/challenging question...'  I recommend Tofic to pay attention to the recommendations and do his best!

Tofik has improved a lot of the points mentioned by the previous interviewer. But still there are things to be improved: 1) expand your self-presentation with the info about the current project as the self-presentation was quite short in general; 2) when talking about serious difficulties - it's necessary to follow STAR model; 3) say how the work on the weaknesses is being done; 4) show interest while talking with the customer as well as while listening to the customer.

Vitaly is a candidate with nice soft skills and he is ready to keep the conversation going. He has well-structured self-presentation, it is detailed and has all relevant information. Vitaly's English level is good enough to support the conversation without any problems. Some points to pay attention to: 1)remember to ask polite return questions to the interviewer  2)avoid using the words 'kinda/like' 3)mind pronunciation of the words ' e-commerce, technique, function'. I wish Vitaly good luck!

Aliaksander is 60% ready for an interview. Quite confident in giving his opinion, expanding on his experience. What to improve: use closing phrases (for example, at the end of the self-presentation); give more exact examples from his work experience.

Большой опыт проектов из разных сфер (образовательный, металлургия и др.). Активно взаимодействовал с заказчиком опыт сбора требований (интервью, изучение бизнес-процессов). Работал как системным аналитиком, так и PM (декомпозиция задач). Прорабатывал UX-прототипы, взаимодействовал с дизайнером при проработке итогового интерфейса. Работал по SCRUM методологии (есть опыт проведения мероприятий). Вел задачи в JIRA. Вел базу знаний в confluence. Использовал BPMN, UML при написании документов. Есть опты работы с микросервисной архитектурой (правда поверхностный). Опыт работы с mySql (умеет выполнять select, join), опыт описания базы с использованием диаграммы классов, при взаимодействии с разработчиком проектировали доработки в БД.

Слабые стороны:
Довольно поверхностное знание REST (мало опыта). Небольшой опыт в интеграционных проектах: при обсуждении не смог выделить основные способы интеграций, рассказать про шину данных. Знания в архитектуре неуверенные: про микросервисную в целом с натяжкой рассказал, про SOA не смог. Не смог рассказать про очереди сообщений и их применение. 
В целом чувствуется что есть опыт и софт скиллы неплохие, рассуждает вполне корректно, нужно подтянуть технические моменты, подробней в рекомендациях ниже.
